<DATE1>  31 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   IFP Reacts to State of Emergency Declaration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IFP Reacts to State of Emergency Declaration </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Buthelezi Views Action as `Invasion' </H4>

<F P=102> MB3103103294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1023 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB3103103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Durban March 31 SAPA -- Inkatha Freedom Party [IFP] 
leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi said on Thursday [31 March] the 
imposition of a state of emergency in Natal/kwaZulu would be 
perceived as an invasion and would render free and fair 
elections impossible. 
  He said the declaration of an emergency proved the 
constitutional process was flawed, adding it marked another 
"chapter of oppression". 
  Troops pouring into kwaZulu would be seen as an "invasion". 
  "We'll see it as an invasion especially if... soldiers and 
army tanks will be rolling in here. It looks like an invasion... 
as if we're being forced by the barrel of a gun." 
  Interviewed at a Durban hotel after a telephone conversation 
with State President F.W. de Klerk, who announced the state of 
emergency on Tuesday [as received] morning, a solemn Mr 
Buthelezi said he was "not happy with it at all". 
  "I would understand his actions if he... considered 
postponing elections for a month or so," said Mr Buthelezi. 
  "I can't see how elections can be free and fair under a 
state 
of emergency." 
  "I told (Mr de Klerk) it was embarrassing," he said, 
explaining he was surprised at the declaration before next 
week's summit meeting between himself, Mr de Klerk, African 
National Congress leader Nelson Mandela and Zulu King Goodwill 
Zwelithini. 
  "It's sort of humiliating. People won't understand it on the 
ground," he said. 
  "I believe tanks will be rolling in, coming from all over," 
he added. 
  Mr Buthelezi said the emergency appeared to be a "form of 
duress for those of us who don't want to participate". 
  "I think this vindicates the point the IFP made: that the 
constitutional process was flawed... that's why we could not get 
our people to participate (in elections). 
  "Everything that has happened completely justifies our 
stance 
and it vindicates us." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

