<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Natal Police To Prepare for Action Under Declaration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Natal Police To Prepare for Action Under Declaration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB3103144694 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1359 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB3103144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Durban March 31 SAPA -- Natal security forces, 
including the kwaZulu Police [KZP], are due to hold a meeting in 
Durban on Friday [1 April] to discuss policing in the province 
under the state of emergency announced by State President F.W. 
de Klerk on Thursday. 
  According to KZP Commissioner Lt-Gen Roy During, the 
emergency regulations would be known on Friday and they would be 
discussed in a meeting between himself and leaders of the SA 
Police and SA Defence Force. "We have to discuss the precise 
nature of the regulations. It's obviously of necessity and our 
policing methods will have to be adapted because it becomes law 
and you have to abide by that," Gen During said. 
  The KZP worked in "close conjunction" with other security 
forces and Friday's meeting would definitely arrive at joint 
policing strategies for certain areas, he said. 
  The emergency would probably allow greater movement to 
security forces and give them greater access to violence 
flash-points, he added. "It may have the effect of stabilising 
the situation, and we sincerely hope that it will have that 
effect." 
  Gen During said he did not expect Inkatha leader Mangosuthu 
Buthelezi, as kwaZulu minister of police, to defy the emergency 
because it was the law and Mr Buthelezi was a "Christian and 
law-abiding citizen". 

</TEXT>

