<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   SADF Expects Good Response to Election Call-Up </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SADF Expects Good Response to Election Call-Up </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB3003195194 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1832 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB3003195194 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by N Patterton] </F>
  [Text] Pretoria March 30 SAPA -- The South African Defence 
Force [SADF] expects a good response to the call-up of Citizen's 
Force and Commando members for the election period. SADF 
Communications Chief Director Maj-Gen Gert Opperman said on 
Wednesday [30 March] predictions of a turn-out of as low as five 
per cent were hopelessly exaggerated. 
  Last year 49 per cent of part-time SADF members reported for 
service when called up, and only 10.6 percent failed to report 
for duty. Others obtained exemption, served in crucial posts or 
could not be traced, said Gen Opperman. 
  The election call-up period is from April 15 to May 15. 
  Gen Opperman said he wanted to stop predictions of a low 
response rate because this could lead to its realisation. "I 
can't see how such predictions can be made. If people stop 
creating a negative perception, and concentrate on the positive, 
we can expect a good number of men." 
  The call-up had the approval of most parties, including the 
End Conscription Campaign and the African National Congress, he 
said. "They are all saying that the chaps should report. The 
call-up is truly in the national interest and for ensuring free 
and fair elections. I think people will react responsibly 
despite their personal fears because this will be in South 
Africa's macro-security interests." 
  Part-time force members would get salaries equalling those 
of 
their permanent force colleagues during the call-up period. 
Subject to approval, the SADF would also pay an allowance to 
them and permanent force members deployed to assist the police. 
  Asked about concerns about the party-political loyalties of 
part-time SADF members and units, Gen Opperman said: "We have 
total confidence in the members of our part-time forces and 
think they will react very responsibly without allowing party 
politics to influence their judgment." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

