<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   ECOWAS Chairman Clarifies Stand on Disputed Posts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ECOWAS Chairman Clarifies Stand on Disputed Posts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB3103110794 Monrovia Radio ELBC in English 0900 GMT 31 Mar 
94 </F>

<F P=103> AB3103110794 </F>
<F P=104>  Monrovia Radio ELBC </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Council of State, the Liberian National 
Transitional Government, has expressed satisfaction over the 
clarifications provided it this week by the chairman of ECOWAS 
[Economic Community of West African States], President Nicephore 
Dieudonne Soglo of the Republic of Benin, relative to the issue 
of the allocation of the Ministries of Foreign Affairs, Finance, 
Justice, and Defense. 
  In a letter to the chairman of the Council of State, 
Professor David Kpomakpor, dated 23 March, Chairman Soglo of 
ECOWAS says that he has learned that a letter bearing his 
signature has been circulated to the leaders of the former 
Liberian factions party to the Cotonou Peace Accord recommending 
that two of the four disputed ministries be given to the NPFL 
[National Patriotic Front of Liberia]. The ECOWAS chairman 
expressed surprise at what he described as an irresponsible act 
because the contents of the purported letter differ totally from 
his recommendations concerning the allocation of the four 
cabinet posts. The ECOWAS chairman reiterated his position that 
the decision for the allocation of the four ministries rests 
with the Liberian people. Chairman Soglo has, therefore, urged 
a prompt settlement of the issue in a spirit of dialogue, 
concerted efforts, good judgment, and secrecy. 

</TEXT>

