<F P=100> SOUTHERN AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Angola </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Political Opposition Party Established </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Political Opposition Party Established </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0204204494 Luanda Radio Nacional Network in Portuguese 
1900 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0204204494 </F>
<F P=104>  Luanda Radio Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Angolan opposition will soon have a new party. 
It is the CDA, Angolan Democratic Confederation. The party, 
which is still making arrangements for registration with the 
Supreme Tribunal, has said the Popular Movement for the 
Liberation of Angola and the National Union for the Total 
Independence of Angola [UNITA] cannot be the only political 
parties in the country. Gaspar Neto, chairman of the CDA's 
constituent commission, felt indignant when he said: 
  [Begin Neto recording] The Angolan problem will not be 
resolved by only those two political forces. [end recording] 
  Gaspar Neto is a man of few words but feels distressed with 
the crisis that has brought the country to its knees. He did 
not announce an immediate solution to the country's problems, 
but said nobody should be in power for ever. 
  [Begin Neto recording] Parties cannot aspire to power the 
moment they come into being. We will learn from Angolan and 
international experiences. At the right moment we will disclose 
to Angola and the world the CDA's plans to gain power. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

