<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-065 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Union Threatens To Strike Over Salaries </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Union Threatens To Strike Over Salaries </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0404195794 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1909 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0404195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cape Town April 4 SAPA -- The South African Police 
Union [SAPU] has threatened to strike unless member salaries are 
increased to the levels of the National Peace Keeping Force 
[NPKF]. Lt-Col Andy Miller, SAPU national and Western Cape 
president, said on Monday [4 April] that members were prepared 
to "sacrifice the election" if their demands for wage parity 
were not implemented by April 13. 
  The union, which represents 20,000 members, made the threat 
despite a Transitional Executive Council (TEC) proposal to 
treble police salaries from R22.50 [rands] to R61.50. The TEC 
Law and Order Sub-committee is expected to hear the proposal on 
Thursday. Col Miller said, however, that a crippling strike on 
the eve of the election could only be averted if police were 
paid the same as their NPKF counterparts, many of whom earned 
double. "I wouldn't call that blackmail. I'd call it justice. 
We've been treated like animals," he said. He said the TEC's 
proposed increases would fail to match those of the NPKF, whose 
members would earn an additional R35 per day once they were 
deployed. 
  "We will not allow policemen to strike," Law and Order 
Ministry spokesman Craig Kotze said on Thursday. He said there 
was "no reason" for a stoppage and "all channels were in place" 
for policemen to air their grievances. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-219 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drafr065_c_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-AFR-94-065 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Holomisa Promises To Disarm SADF Citizen Force </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Holomisa Promises To Disarm SADF Citizen Force </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0404153294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1428 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0404153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ben Maclennan] </F>
  [Text] East London April 4 SAPA -- President F W de Klerk 
should tell kwaZulu Chief Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi to stop 
his nonsense because the African National Congress was not 
prepared to postpone the election, Major-General Bantu Holomisa 
said on Monday. Gen Holomisa, who heads Transkei's Military 
Council and is also a senior ANC candidate for the National 
Assembly, was speaking to about 4,000 people at an ANC rally in 
a sports stadium at Duncan Village, East London. The rally was 
shifted at the last minute from a venue in a community hall when 
it became clear that the hall could not accommodate the number 
of people who wanted to hear him. 
  Gen Holomisa said kwaZulu was under President de Klerk's 
jurisdiction. "He must not create an impression that kwaZulu is 
an independent state. It is him personally who must see there 
is stability in that area." 
  The ANC was not impressed by Mr de Klerk's attempts to draw 
its president Mr Nelson Mandela and other people into the 
conflict. "All he must do is to tell Buthelezi that the nonsense 
must stop now, and it must stop as soon as possible, because we 
are not prepared to postpone the elections in South Africa 
because of one man." 
  Gen Holomisa also said under a new government, all weapons, 
which had been handed over by the state to whites "under the 
pretext of self defence", would be confiscated and returned to 
armouries. This included weaponry issued to SADF [South African 
Defense Force] Citizen Force Commandos. It was these weapons 
which had been used to kill people in Bophuthatswana. There 
were also people in the community who owned illegal weapons. 
"We must come up with a campaign to make sure we demilitarise 
our population," he said. Ordinary citizens who had licensed 
private firearms would be allowed to keep them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

