<H3> <TI>   International Mediation Postponed One Week </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    International Mediation Postponed One Week </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MB0504115294 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1121 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0504115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by C. Govender] </F>
  [Text] Durban April 5 SAPA -- The African National Congress 
and the Inkatha Freedom Party [IFP] jointly announced on Tuesday 
[5 April] that international mediation scheduled for Thursday 
has been postponed to next week. The move is to clear the way 
for a summit between ANC President Nelson Mandela, IFP leader 
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, Zulu King Goodwill Zwelithini and State 
President F W de Klerk. 
  A joint statement said progress with the international 
mediation was "assessed in the context of current developments". 
"In the light of the pending summit of leaders on Friday, the 
meeting decided to delay the start of the mediation until next 
week. 
  "It is hoped the leaders' summit will help build consensus 
on 
the purpose and terms of reference of the international 
mediation." 
  Mediators were being informed of the decision, the statement 
concluded. 
  Senior ANC and IFP officials, meeting at the World Trade 
Centre in Kempton Park [words indistinct] mediation. 

</TEXT>

