Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Togo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lack of Quorum in Parliament; Koffigoh Absent </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lack of Quorum in Parliament; Koffigoh Absent </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0504164594 Libreville Africa No. 1 in French 1215 GMT 5 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0504164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Libreville Africa No. 1 </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The first ordinary session of the Togolese National 
Assembly could not begin this morning as scheduled due to lack 
of quorum. Not all opposition deputies showed up at the 
assembly session. Another conspicuous absence was that of 
outgoing Prime Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh. From Lome, 
Olabire da Cruz reports: 
  [Begin Da Cruz recording] Only 37 out of the remaining 78 
deputies responded to the invitation to attend the National 
Assembly session this morning, which was convened by the 
chairman and most senior assembly man, Ayitoh Kossi of the 
Action Committee for Renewal, who was himself absent in line 
with the joint decision of his party, the Togolese Union for 
Democracy, to suspend opposition deputies' participation in the 
National Assembly deliberations until the Supreme Court 
clarifies its decision to invalidate the election of three 
deputies of the parliamentary majority. 
  Following the lack of quorum, the 37 deputies of the Rally 
of 
the Togolese People [RPT] and the Union for Justice and 
Development, the RPT's ally, left the National Assembly, noting 
with regret the absence of their 40 opposition colleagues. 
  The outgoing prime minister, the only elected candidate and 
leader of the Coordination of New Forces, was also absent from 
the session. Sources close to the prime minister's office said 
however that the reason for his absence is quite different from 
that of the opposition deputies. 
  We note that this morning's session was notably to allow 
deputies to discuss the assembly's standing orders. The 
referent documents on the standing orders were distributed to 
the parliamentarians on 30 March for prior study. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

