<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Gabon </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Oye-Mba's 4th Cabinet Assumes Office </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Oye-Mba's 4th Cabinet Assumes Office </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB0504214994 Libreville Africa No. 1 in French 1830 GMT 5 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0504214994 </F>
<F P=104>  Libreville Africa No. 1 </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Gabon, Prime Minister Casimir Oye-Mba's fourth 
government assumed office officially in Libreville this 
afternoon about 10 days after it was formed. Addressing the 36 
members of his cabinet, Prime Minister Oye-Mba did not fail to 
point out the difficulties that might crop up during their terms 
of office. Let us listen to Mr. Oye-Mba: 
  [Begin Oye-Mba recording] Apart from the pride generated in 
you by your appointment, you should know that being a cabinet 
member is mainly a question of office and responsibility. I 
inform you, particularly the newcomers, that the president of 
the Republic and I did not call on you to attend a picnic. We 
called on you to assume heavy and difficult responsibilities. I 
sincerely congratulate and encourage you. I assure you of my 
personal support which will help you do your work in accordance 
with the head of state's general guidelines and the instructions 
that I will give you. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

